# 🚀 feature request

### Relevant Package

This feature request is for `@angular/router`.


### Description

Lazy loading is possible with the following use of the `RouterModule`:
```ts
        RouterModule.forChild([
            {
                path: "lazy",
                loadChildren: () =>
                    import("./lazy.module").then(
                        (m) => m.LazyModule
                    ),
            },
        ]),
```

We build the `lazy.module.ts` and publish it as an npm package with `ng-packagr`. Then we import the npm package in the following way for lazy loading:
```ts
        RouterModule.forChild([
            {
                path: "lazy",
                loadChildren: () =>
                    import("lazy-module").then(
                        (m) => m.LazyModule
                    ),
            },
        ]),
```
This does not work.

### Describe the solution you'd like

We'd like that the following import works:
```ts
        RouterModule.forChild([
            {
                path: "lazy",
                loadChildren: () =>
                    import("lazy-module").then( // "lazy-module" is an npm package
                        (m) => m.LazyModule
                    ),
            },
        ]),
```

### Describe alternatives you've considered
At the moment, we are using the following workaround. We wrap the npm module in an angular module and import it. This leads to a significant increase of code, as most of our modules are published to a npm registry and imported that way.
```ts
import {NgModule} from "@angular/core";
import {LazyModule} from "lazy-module";

@NgModule({
    imports: [
        LazyModule
    ],
})
export class WrapperLazyModule {}
```

# 🚀 feature request

### Relevant Package
<!-- Can you pin-point one or more @angular/* packages the are relevant for this feature request? -->
<!-- ✍️edit: --> This feature request is for @angular/core


### Description
```
export class BaseComponent {
}

@Component({
  selector: 'derived1',
  template: `<p>Derived Component 1</p>`,
  providers: [{ provide: BaseComponent, useExisting: DerivedComponent1 }]
})
export class DerivedComponent1 extends BaseComponent {
}

@Component({
  selector: 'derived2',
  template: `<p>Derived Component 2</p>`,
  providers: [{ provide: BaseComponent, useExisting: DerivedComponent2}]
})
export class DerivedComponent2 {
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app',
  template: `
  <derived1></derived1>
  <derived2></derived2>
`
})
export class AppComponent implements AfterViewInit {
@ViewChildren(BaseComponent) children: QueryList<BaseComponent>;

  ngAfterViewInit() {
    console.log(this.children);
  }
}
```
In this example I have `DerivedComponent1` which extends `BaseComponent` and `DerivedComponent2` which does not. 
Both get populated in the `children` query list because they each have a provider declaration for `BaseComponent`.

**Issue:** Is there a way I can declare all providers for BaseComponent at once? Something like:
```
const derivedComponents = [ DerivedComponent1, DerivedComponent2 ];
@Component({
  selector: 'app',
  template: `
  <derived1></derived1>
  <derived2></derived2>
`,
 providers: derivedComponents.map(component => ({ provide: BaseComponent, useExisting: component }))
})
export class AppComponent implements AfterViewInit {
@ViewChildren(BaseComponent) children: QueryList<BaseComponent>;

  ngAfterViewInit() {
    console.log(this.children);
  }
}
```

I've tried this but `children` comes back empty.

### Referenced Issues:
https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/8580
https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/18700

Thanks in advance!

